s historical importance, making use of the latest empirical research and revisionist theories, and concentrating on people and personalities, perceptions and expectations, rather than dry constitutional analysis. Papers consider both the institutional and the personal facets of Edward II's life and rule: his sexual reputation, the royal court, the role of the king's household knights, the nature of law and parliament in the reign, and England's relations with Ireland and Europe. Contributors: J.S. HAMILTON, W.M. ORMROD, IAN MORTIMER, MICHAEL PRESTWICH, ALISTAIR TEBBIT, W.R. CHILDS, PAUL DRYBURGH, ANTHONY MUSSON, GWILYM DODD, ALISON MARSHALL, MARTYN LAWRENCE, SEYMOUR PHILLIPS.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aEdward II's reign.  aEdward II.  aEurope.  aIreland.  aclass relations.  aeconomic change.  amonarchy.  asociety.1 aChilds, W. R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChilds, Wendy R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDodd, Gwilym, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDodd, Gwilym, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDryburgh, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, J. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJ.S. Hamilton, Jeffrey S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawrence, Martyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarshall, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMortimer, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMusson, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMusson, Anthony,